data.content:
Yes — for simple inline data, use `[DataRow]` instead. It's cleaner and type-safe:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

If you need **computed or complex test data** (where `DataRow` won't work since it requires compile-time constants), use strongly-typed tuples instead of `object[]`:

```csharp
public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];

[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected((string Input, bool Expected) testCase)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(testCase.Input);
    Assert.AreEqual(testCase.Expected, result);
}
```

**Summary:** `DataRow` → simple literals. `DynamicData` with tuples/records → complex or computed data. Both avoid the untyped `object[]` problem.
